{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533104"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:32:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:32:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14752"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14752"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.39,0.08,0.24,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7443"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58424"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7443"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14752"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43840"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"302"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1359"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4034"},{"type":"tags","id":"4606"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18219"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49755"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58424"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man is admitted to the Intensive Care Unit with severe community-acquired pneumonia. He has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His regular medications are metformin, perindopril, and amlodipine. He is currently intubated and mechanically ventilated with vasopressor support.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is irregular at 170/min, blood pressure 105/50 mmHg on noradrenaline 2 mcg/min, respiratory rate 16/min (ventilated), SpO2 94% on FiO2 0.5, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. An ECG shows atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diltiazem infusion","Electrical cardioversion","Digoxin loading dose","Metoprolol infusion","Amiodarone infusion"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with new-onset atrial fibrillation in the context of critical illness. The rapid ventricular rate and underlying sepsis are likely compromising cardiac output, necessitating vasopressor support. In critically ill patients, rhythm control is often preferred over rate control to optimise haemodynamics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmiodarone infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is the most first line appropriate choice for an ICU patient with AF as it provides both rate and rhythm control with minimal negative inotropic effects. It is particularly useful in critically ill patients as it has less impact on blood pressure compared to other antiarrhythmics. Amiodarone can typically only be given as an intravenous infusion in higher monitoring areas (such as ICU, HDU or CCU). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigoxin\u003C/strong\u003E has a delayed onset of action and is less effective in the presence of high sympathetic tone, as seen in critical illness. It also provides rate control only, without addressing the underlying rhythm disturbance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E and other beta-blockers can worsen hypotension in septic patients due to their negative inotropic effects. They are generally avoided in patients requiring vasopressor support.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiltiazem\u003C/strong\u003E, like other calcium channel blockers, has significant negative inotropic effects and can worsen hypotension in critically ill patients. It is more appropriate for rate control in stable patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectrical cardioversion\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if the patient had worsening haemodynamic instability. In this case, the patient is maintaining adequate blood pressure on moderate vasopressor support (in the setting of sepsis and being sedated/intubated), making pharmacological management a more appropriate first line given the risks associated with electrical cardioversion. Ideally, an echocardiograph should be obtained prior to exclude the presence of an atrial thrombus. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Amiodarone is first-line therapy for acute atrial fibrillation in critically ill patients due to its efficacy and minimal negative inotropic effects.","Rate control alone may be appropriate in stable patients but rhythm control is often preferred in critical illness to optimise cardiac output.","Ideally an echocardiograph should be obtained prior to electrical cardioversion to exclude the presence of an atrial thrombus."],"references":["Bosch NA, Cimini J, Walkey AJ. Atrial Fibrillation in the ICU. Chest. 2018 Dec;154(6):1424-1434. doi: 10.1016/j.chest.2018.03.040. Epub 2018 Apr 6. PMID: 29627355; PMCID: PMC6335260.","Arrigo M, Bettex D, Rudiger A. Management of atrial fibrillation in critically ill patients. Crit Care Res Pract. 2014;2014:840615. https://doi.org/10.1155/2014/840615."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43840"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14752"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43840"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-31T16:26:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T16:29:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7443"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58424"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":